FILL_CH9 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>Paul opens with a rhetorical cluster of four questions: 'Am I not free? Am I not an apostle? Have I not seen Jesus our Lord?' The apostolic claim rests on the resurrection appearance — <em>heōraka</em> ('I have seen') in the perfect tense records a past event with continuing present significance. Paul's authority to speak about apostolic rights, eucharistic practices, and resurrection (ch. 15) flows from this founding encounter with the risen Lord. Every apostolic credential Paul defends in this chapter is underwritten by the resurrection.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Corinthians themselves are the 'seal' (<em>sphragis</em>) of Paul's apostleship 'in the Lord' — their very existence as a Christian community authenticates the apostolic mission. In ancient commerce and law, a seal verified the authenticity and ownership of a document or container. The risen Lord's work through Paul's proclamation is the living authentication — the Corinthians are not merely Paul's product but Christ's possession, as Paul will say later (3:23: 'you are Christ's').</p>",
    "3": "<p>Paul's defense (<em>apologia</em>) of his apostolic rights is simultaneously a defense of the gospel pattern: the one sent by a greater authority has the right to be sustained by those he serves. The legal terminology reflects the Roman judicial culture of Corinth, but the underlying reality is theological: the apostle's commission comes from Christ, and Christ's pattern of providing for those he commissions is the basis for the rights Paul then voluntarily surrenders.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The right to eat and drink at community expense is the most basic apostolic right, grounded in the Lord's command (v. 14). Paul names it first before surrendering it. The question of who has the right to be sustained by whom reverses the patron-client hierarchy: the apostle sent by the ultimate Patron (Christ) has claims on the community that cultural conventions about dependency would complicate. Paul navigates this by having the right but not exercising it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The right to bring a 'believing wife' (<em>adelphē gynaika</em>, literally 'sister-wife') on mission reflects the married apostolic pattern — Peter and the other apostles and brothers of the Lord traveled with their wives. The 'believing' qualifier marks the wife as a fellow member of the Christ-community, a sister in the Lord, not merely a social accompaniment. The new social bonds created by Christ ('brother,' 'sister') redefine even the most intimate natural bonds.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Barnabas, Paul's early missionary partner, is cited as sharing the practice of not taking support. The reference assumes the Corinthians know Barnabas — he was part of the early mission trajectory that led to Corinth. The partnership between Paul and Barnabas (Acts 13-14; Gal 2:1-9) is a model of the team apostolate in which Christ's mission was carried through collaborative voluntary sacrifice, not individual heroes demanding their due.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Three analogies — soldier, vine-grower, shepherd — all argue from universal practice: workers in every field are sustained by their labor. Paul uses creation-level arguments (all workers are supported) before moving to scriptural arguments (v. 9-13). The deepest logic behind all three analogies is the pattern of the creator God who sustains those who work in his field: the Messiah feeds those he sends, as God fed the Levites through the sacrificial system.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Does not the Law say the same?' — Paul moves from creation analogy to Torah precedent, signaling that the Torah's deepest meaning is not merely legal regulation but theological pattern. The Torah speaks 'for our sake' (v. 10) — a hermeneutical principle that Paul will elaborate: the OT's ethical and narrative content is addressed to the new covenant community who stand at the fulfillment of what the Torah anticipated.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The command 'Do not muzzle the ox while it treads out the grain' (Deut 25:4) is reinterpreted: 'Is it for oxen that God is concerned?' Paul's question is not dismissive of animal welfare but typological: the commandment points beyond livestock to the principle that the laborer shares in the fruit of the labor. The law's concern is ultimately for 'us' — those who plow and thresh in the Lord's harvest field, which Paul has been doing in Corinth. The Torah was written looking forward to the community of Christ.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'It was written for our sake, because the plowman should plow in hope and the thresher thresh in hope of sharing in the crop.' The eschatological hope that motivates all labor — the anticipation of harvest — maps onto apostolic labor: Paul plows and threshes the gospel field with the hope of the eschatological harvest. This is the Christological reframing of OT commands: they were written not merely for Israelite agricultural society but as instructions for the community of Christ who work in hope of the final harvest.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'If we have sown spiritual things among you, is it too much if we reap your material things?' The spiritual/material exchange reflects the incarnational economy: Christ himself entered the material world to sow the spiritual — eternal life — and the apostolic mission continues this pattern. The community that has received the imperishable (the gospel, the Spirit, resurrection hope) owes material support to those who brought it. The exchange is asymmetric: the spiritual gift vastly exceeds the material return.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Paul's decision not to use his right is for the sake of 'the gospel of Christ' — explicitly christologically motivated. He endures everything to 'put no obstacle in the way of the gospel.' The gospel's credibility depends on its proclamation not being monetized; Paul's voluntary poverty demonstrates that the message is not a commercial enterprise. This pattern of suffering for the gospel's integrity mirrors Christ's own refusal to use divine prerogative for self-advancement (2 Cor 8:9).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Temple workers sharing in the sacrificial system is the final OT precedent before the Lord's direct command (v. 14). The Levitical priests who served at the altar ate from the altar (Lev 7:6; Num 18:8-20). The sacrificial economy is a type: Christ the high priest has established a new sacrificial system in which those who serve receive sustenance. Paul, as a minister of the new covenant's 'altar' (the gospel), has the right to be sustained by those who benefit from the sacrifice he proclaims.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'In the same way, the Lord commanded that those who proclaim the gospel should get their living by the gospel.' The command comes from Jesus himself (cf. Luke 10:7; Matt 10:10), placing the apostolic support-right directly in the Lord's authority. Paul's voluntary surrender of this right is therefore a deliberate departure from the Lord's provision — not disobedience but an intensification of service that even exceeds what the Lord's command requires. The apostle's kenosis mirrors and extends the Lord's own pattern.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Paul's boast (<em>kauchēma</em>) in free proclamation is grounded not in his own achievement but in the grace that made him an apostle (v. 17). Yet the boast is real: Paul has chosen something beyond the minimum required. The Christological parallel is the Son's assumption of human poverty (2 Cor 8:9) as a choice beyond what the Father required — love that exceeds obligation. Paul's apostolic boast participates in the logic of grace that exceeds requirement.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'For if I preach the gospel, that gives me no ground for boasting, for necessity is laid upon me' — the compulsion to preach is not mechanical but vocational. The 'necessity' (<em>anagkē</em>) reflects the prophetic compulsion: the prophet cannot not speak when the word of the Lord comes (cf. Jer 20:9; Amos 3:8). For Paul, the word of Christ (the risen Lord's Damascus road appearance) functions as the irreversible commission that defines his identity and cannot be refused without catastrophic personal consequence.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Paul is a 'steward' (<em>oikonomos</em>) entrusted with the gospel. The steward manages the master's household resources but has no ultimate claim on them — he is accountable to the master, not to those he serves. The gospel Paul manages is Christ's possession, delivered to Paul as a trust. The oikonomos metaphor implies that the gospel's content, form, and distribution are determined by the master (Christ), not by the steward's preferences or the audience's demands.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Paul's reward (<em>misthos</em>) is the very act of presenting the gospel free of charge — the reward is in the preaching itself, not in the material return. This is the Christological logic of the kingdom economy: the one who gives up material advantage for the sake of the kingdom is already in possession of the kingdom's treasure. The free gospel reflects the free gift of grace; charging for it would compromise the character of the message itself.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Though I am free from all, I have made myself a slave to all, that I might win more of them.' This is the clearest apostolic echo of the incarnational pattern: the one who is free (divine, elevated, not obligated) voluntarily becomes a servant of all for the purpose of saving many. Paul's self-description here mirrors the Christological hymn of Phil 2:5-11: 'he emptied himself, taking the form of a servant.' The apostle's kenotic mission-strategy is not mere pragmatism but a Christological way of being in the world.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'To the Jews I became as a Jew, in order to win Jews.' Paul's accommodation to Jewish practice (circumcising Timothy, Acts 16:3; taking a Nazirite vow, Acts 18:18) is not syncretism but missional identification. The incarnational pattern licenses it: the eternal Son became 'born under the law, to redeem those who were under the law' (Gal 4:4-5). Mission through identification — taking on the other's condition — is the Christological form of apostolic work.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'To those outside the law I became as one outside the law' — Paul's freedom from Torah observance when engaging Gentiles mirrors the radical cultural flexibility of the incarnation. The Son entered a specific first-century Jewish context to be 'to the Jew first,' but the gospel is 'also to the Greek' (Rom 1:16). The apostle who is 'not outside the law of God but under the law of Christ' (<em>ennomos Christou</em>) embodies a new law — love — that encompasses both Torah-observance and Torah-freedom.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'To the weak I became weak, that I might win the weak.' The kenotic identification with weakness is the Christological signature of Paul's apostolate: 'he was crucified in weakness, yet he lives by the power of God' (2 Cor 13:4). The cross is the supreme act of becoming weak: the eternal power of God takes the form of crucified human weakness. Paul's apostolic weakness is not a deficiency to be overcome but a participation in the Christological mode of redemption.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'I do it all for the sake of the gospel, that I may share in its blessings.' The apostle's participation in the gospel blessings is not guaranteed by status or inheritance but by active gospel-partnership. Paul is not merely a conveyor of grace but a sharer in it — the same grace he proclaims sustains and transforms him. The 'blessings' (<em>synkoinōnos autou</em>, co-participant with it) point to the eschatological harvest: the apostle shares in the reaping of the souls he has won through his labor.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Do you not know that in a race all the runners run, but only one receives the prize? So run that you may obtain it.' The athletic metaphor frames the Christian life as purposeful, disciplined pursuit — not casual participation but focused effort toward the goal. The 'prize' (<em>brabeion</em>) in the Corinthian context would evoke the Isthmian games held near Corinth. Paul's Christian race has a specific finish line: the final day when Christ will be revealed and the prize given to those who have persevered.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Every athlete exercises self-control in all things. They do it to receive a perishable wreath, but we an imperishable.' The Isthmian victor's crown was a wreath of pine or celery — beautiful, honored, and then withered. The imperishable crown (<em>aphtharton stephanos</em>) anticipates Paul's resurrection-glory language in ch. 15: the body raised in imperishability (<em>aphtharsian</em>) is the same quality as the crown awarded for faithful discipleship. The athletic prize is a Christological trophy — won by Christ's victory over death and shared with those who run with him.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'So I do not run aimlessly; I do not box as one beating the air.' Paul's self-discipline is purposeful (<em>houtōs trechō hōs ouk adēlōs</em>) — he runs with a specific destination and strikes with precision, not shadow-boxing. The Christian life, modeled on the apostolic example, is teleologically structured: there is a goal, a judge, and a prize. The coming judgment-seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10) gives Christian labor its ultimate orientation — every act of discipline or sacrifice is an investment in that final accountability.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'I discipline my body and keep it under control, lest after preaching to others I myself should be disqualified.' The apostle who proclaims the gospel is not immune from the possibility of disqualification (<em>adokimos</em>). Paul's bodily discipline reflects the Christian understanding of the body as the site of spiritual warfare, moral formation, and eschatological preparation. The body is not irrelevant (Platonic spiritualism) but is the specific domain in which Christian faithfulness is enacted — a body that will itself be raised and transformed.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH10 = {
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>'Our fathers were all under the cloud and all passed through the sea.' The exodus generation is claimed as corporate ancestor ('our fathers') by Paul — a Gentile-majority community in Corinth. The church, as the new Israel, inherits the typological history of Israel: the exodus story is not alien background but the community's own story, reread through Christ. The cloud (divine presence and guidance) and the sea (the crossing that created the nation) are the foundational saving events that find their antitype in the Spirit and baptism.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'All were baptized into Moses in the cloud and in the sea.' The typological identification of the sea-crossing with baptism uses the same preposition ('into Moses') as 'baptized into Christ' (Rom 6:3; Gal 3:27). Moses as the mediator-representative whom the people were united with typifies Christ — the greater mediator into whom believers are baptized. The cloud as divine Spirit-presence (the pillar of cloud that guided Israel, Exod 13:21-22) also types the Spirit given at Christian baptism. The entire exodus becomes a Christological-pneumatological type.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'All ate the same spiritual food.' The manna that God provided daily in the wilderness (Exod 16) is called 'spiritual food' (<em>pneumatikon broma</em>) — not because it was immaterial but because it was supernaturally given and pointed beyond itself to the true bread from heaven. Jesus in John 6:31-35 explicitly identifies the manna as a type of himself ('I am the bread of life... not like the bread the fathers ate'). The wilderness feeding was a sacramental sign of the Christ who is the ultimate sustainer of God's people.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Nevertheless, with most of them God was not pleased, for they were overthrown in the wilderness.' Despite having all the typological benefits — the Christological cloud, sea-baptism, spiritual food, and spiritual drink — the wilderness generation perished. The warning is stark: sacramental participation does not guarantee salvation. The Corinthians who received baptism and ate the Lord's Supper could not rest on these as automatic guarantees of standing before God, any more than the wilderness generation could rest on the exodus.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Now these things took place as examples (<em>typoi</em>) for us, that we might not desire evil as they did.' Paul explicitly names the hermeneutical principle: the wilderness events were <em>typoi</em> — patterns, prefigurations written into Israel's history with the new covenant community in view. The typological reading is not allegorization but a claim about God's providential structuring of Israel's history: the wilderness generation enacted patterns of failure that the Christ-community must avoid. Desire for evil was Israel's root failure; the same root still threatens the church.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Do not be idolaters as some of them were; as it is written, \'The people sat down to eat and drink and rose up to play.\'' The golden calf episode (Exod 32:6) — Israel's great apostasy from covenant loyalty at the very moment of Moses's mediatorial absence receiving the Torah — provides the type for Corinthian compromise with idol-food culture. The eating and drinking 'at play' (<em>paizein</em>) at the golden calf parallels the Corinthian temple banquets. The Christ who has established the new covenant is dishonored when his people participate in the worship of rivals.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'We must not indulge in sexual immorality as some of them did, and twenty-three thousand fell in a single day.' The reference is to the Baal Peor incident (Num 25:1-9) where Israel joined in the sexual cult associated with Moabite worship. The Christological application: Christ as the divine husband of Israel (and now the church) is jealous for his people's exclusive covenant loyalty. Sexual immorality in the Corinthian context (temple prostitution as part of the Aphrodite cult) was not merely personal sin but covenantal adultery against the Lord who redeemed them.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'We must not put Christ to the test, as some of them did and were destroyed by serpents.' The 'testing' at Massah-Meribah (Num 21:4-6; cf. Ps 95:8-9) where Israel complained against God's provision is applied to 'Christ' — a striking theological claim. Paul assumes Christ's divine pre-existence: the 'Lord' who was tested in the wilderness is the pre-incarnate Christ (connecting to v. 4: 'the rock was Christ'). The Corinthians who tested God's patience with their eucharistic abuses were testing Christ himself.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Nor grumble, as some of them did and were destroyed by the Destroyer.' The wilderness murmuring traditions (Num 11:1; 14:2; 16:41) are warnings for the Corinthian community whose divisions (1:10-12) and complaints about Paul (4:18-19) echo the wilderness pattern. The 'Destroyer' (<em>olothreutēs</em>) evokes the destroyer angel of the Passover (Exod 12:23) and the judgment at Korah's rebellion (Num 16:41-50). Christ who delivered Israel from the destroying angel is also the judge who exercises judgment through discipline (v. 22).</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Now these things happened to them as an example, but they were written down for our instruction, on whom the end of the ages has come.' The Christological hermeneutic is explicit: the OT was written <em>for us</em>, the community living at 'the ends of the ages' (<em>ta telē tōn aiōnōn</em>). Paul locates the church at the eschatological junction where all prior history finds its goal. The wilderness generation's stories are not museum pieces but active instruction for those living in the final, decisive act of God's redemptive drama inaugurated in Christ's death and resurrection.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Let anyone who thinks he stands take heed lest he fall.' The warning is addressed to the spiritually self-confident — those who, like the wilderness generation, assume that covenant status guarantees security. The Corinthians who possessed spiritual gifts, baptism, and eucharistic participation were tempted to presumption. The humility this verse calls for is shaped by Christological realism: standing is a position maintained by the faithfulness of the one who holds us, not by our own achieved security.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'God is faithful, and he will not let you be tempted beyond your ability, but with the temptation he will also provide the way of escape (<em>ekbasin</em>), that you may be able to endure it.' The faithfulness of God is the Christological foundation of moral endurance. Christ himself was 'tempted in every way as we are, yet without sin' (Heb 4:15) — in his wilderness temptation (Matt 4:1-11) he passed where Israel failed and blazed the trail that becomes the <em>ekbasis</em> for those who are in him. The way of escape is not evasion but Christ-shaped endurance.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Therefore, my beloved, flee from idolatry.' The 'therefore' (<em>dioper</em>) — consequential command — follows from the assurance of v. 13: because God provides escape, flee. The command to flee (<em>pheugete</em>) is urgent and physical — not 'reconsider your theological framework about idols' but 'get out.' The Corinthian practice of attending temple banquets as a matter of social and commercial necessity is incompatible with the exclusive loyalty that Christ requires of those who are bought with his blood (6:20).</p>",
    "15": "<p>'I speak as to sensible people; judge for yourselves what I say.' Paul's appeal to the Corinthians' own judgment (ironically, given his critique of their wisdom-pride) about the eucharistic theology he is about to articulate signals confidence in the argument's self-evidence. Those who have received the Spirit — and the Corinthians prided themselves on spiritual gifts — should be able to discern the incompatibility between the Lord's table and idols' tables. The appeal to wisdom serves the Christological argument: Christ's presence at the table is real enough to make competing allegiances dangerous.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'The cup of blessing that we bless, is it not a participation (<em>koinōnia</em>) in the blood of Christ? The bread that we break, is it not a participation in the body of Christ?' The eucharistic theology is unambiguous: the Lord's Supper is genuine <em>koinōnia</em> (fellowship, participation, sharing) in the blood and body of Christ. <em>Koinōnia</em> is not merely emotional association but real participation — the same word used for partnership in business and in the gospel (Phil 1:5). The broken bread and poured cup make present the once-for-all sacrifice and effect real participation in its saving benefits.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Because there is one bread, we who are many are one body, for we all partake of the one bread.' The unity of the church derives from the unity of Christ: many members, one bread, one body. The church's unity is not achieved through organizational effort or doctrinal consensus but through Eucharistic participation in the one Christ. The 'one body' here anticipates the body-of-Christ ecclesiology of ch. 12: the church's corporate identity is constituted by the one Christ who is both the bread distributed and the body formed by its reception.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Consider the people of Israel: are not those who eat the sacrifices participants in the altar?' The Levitical sacrificial system provides the type: eating the portion of the sacrifice that was not burned created solidarity with the altar and with the deity to whom it was offered. The priest and worshiper who ate the peace offering (Lev 7:15-18) were participants in the covenant relationship the sacrifice maintained. Paul uses this participatory logic to argue that eating idol-food at temple banquets creates an analogous — and incompatible — participation with what is sacrificed there.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'What do I imply then? That food offered to idols is anything, or that an idol is anything?' Paul's careful qualification prevents misreading: idols are ontologically nothing (as he argued in 8:4-6 — 'there is no God but one'). The problem is not that idol-food has been spiritually contaminated but that eating at the idol's table creates a social and spiritual solidarity with demonic power. The distinction between the ontological status of idols (nothing) and the social/spiritual reality of idol-worship (participation in the demonic) is the key move.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'No, I imply that what pagans sacrifice they offer to demons and not to God.' Paul draws on the Deuteronomy 32:17 tradition ('they sacrificed to demons, not to God') to identify the spiritual reality behind pagan worship: the powers behind the idols are demonic. The idol itself is nothing, but the cult surrounding it is a demonic system. Participation in that system — even incidentally through table fellowship — creates an incompatible allegiance with the Lord whose table the Corinthians also eat at. The demonic and the divine cannot share a patron.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'You cannot drink the cup of the Lord and the cup of demons. You cannot partake of the table of the Lord and the table of demons.' The absolute incompatibility of the two tables is a Christological claim: Christ's lordship is exclusive. The 'Lord's table' is not merely a communal meal but the place of Christ's real presence — where his body and blood are participated in (v. 16). Divided table loyalty is spiritual adultery: the covenant Lord who bought the community with his blood will not share his people with the demonic powers they serve at pagan shrines.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Shall we provoke the Lord to jealousy? Are we stronger than he?' The divine jealousy language comes from Deuteronomy 32:21 — the Song of Moses which describes Israel's apostasy provoking God's jealous wrath. Paul applies this to the Corinthians: they are replaying Israel's wilderness apostasy (the golden calf's eating and drinking, v. 7) by their divided table loyalty. The rhetorical question 'are we stronger than he?' exposes the absurdity of idolatry — choosing the weaker power (demons) over the stronger (the Lord who raises the dead).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'All things are lawful, but not all things are helpful. All things are lawful, but not all things build up.' The libertine slogan ('all things are lawful') that apparently circulated in Corinth (cf. 6:12) is conceded in principle but immediately qualified by the Christological criterion of love: what builds up the community of Christ is the standard, not what the individual's freedom licenses. The freedom Christ won is freedom for love, not freedom from accountability to the body of Christ.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Let no one seek his own good, but the good of his neighbor.' The neighbor-love principle — Lev 19:18, cited by Jesus as the summary of the law alongside love for God (Mark 12:31) — becomes the operative principle for resolving the idol-food question. The 'strong' who have knowledge that idols are nothing must not exercise their knowledge at the expense of the 'weak' whose conscience is damaged by seeing believers eat idol-food. Christ's cross is the ultimate expression of seeking the other's good at the cost of one's own rights.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Eat whatever is sold in the meat market without raising any question on the ground of conscience.' The practical guideline for daily life in a pagan city: do not scruple about meat purchased in the market, since its prior cultic history is irrelevant once it enters normal commercial circulation. The 'earth is the Lord's' (v. 26) means that all created food belongs to God and is available for his people's use — the created world is not under demonic ownership by default. This is the Christological affirmation of creation's goodness despite its contamination by sin.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'For the earth is the Lord's, and everything in it' — a direct citation of Psalm 24:1. The psalm is about the Lord as creator and owner of all creation, applied here as the theological basis for food freedom. Because the Lord (Christ, in Paul's usage) is sovereign over all creation, no created thing is intrinsically polluted. The false dualism that treats the material world as defiled is defeated by the Christological affirmation of creation: the one through whom all things were created (1 Cor 8:6) has not ceded creation's goodness to demonic powers.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'If one of the unbelievers invites you to dinner and you are disposed to go, eat whatever is set before you without raising any question on the ground of conscience.' The practical guideline for social interaction with unbelievers extends the creation-goodness principle: food served in an unbeliever's home is not ceremonially problematic. The mission imperative requires social accessibility — Paul's own 'becoming all things to all people' (9:22) includes willingness to eat with unbelievers without scruple, as a sign of the gospel's world-embracing reach.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'But if someone says to you, \'This has been offered in sacrifice,\' then do not eat it, for the sake of the one who informed you and for the sake of conscience.' The exception: when idol-food's cultic origin is explicitly flagged, the strong believer should decline — not because the food is now spiritually dangerous but because eating in that context, after the cultic association has been made explicit, would signal solidarity with the idol-system to the observer. The other's conscience (whether a weaker believer or a watching unbeliever) governs the strong believer's freedom in Christ.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'I do not mean your own conscience, but his. For why should my liberty be determined by someone else's conscience?' The paradox: Paul defends freedom from others' scruples in principle while arguing for voluntary restraint in practice. The freedom Christ won is not freedom from one another but freedom for one another. True Christological freedom is mature enough to voluntarily limit itself for the sake of those whose faith is weaker — the same pattern as Christ who 'though he was rich became poor' (2 Cor 8:9) for those who were spiritually impoverished.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'If I partake with thankfulness, why am I denounced because of that for which I give thanks?' The thanksgiving principle — eating with gratitude recognizing God as the giver of food (cf. 1 Tim 4:4-5) — is the norm of Christian eating. The Lord who gave every good gift, and whose gift is acknowledged in thanksgiving, is the one who also determines when that gift's use would harm another. Freedom and thankfulness do not override the love-principle that governs all things in Christ.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'So, whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do all to the glory of God.' The comprehensive principle: every act, including the most ordinary (eating and drinking), is to be performed in a way that honors God. The glory of God (<em>doxa Theou</em>) is the Christological criterion for all behavior — the same glory that was revealed in Christ's cross (John 12:23-28) and will be fully revealed at the resurrection (ch. 15). Christian freedom is freedom to glorify God in every act, not freedom from accountability to him.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'Give no offense to Jews or to Greeks or to the church of God.' The universal mission scope: Jews (the covenant people), Greeks (the Gentile world), and the church (the new community in Christ) must not be caused to stumble by the believer's exercise of freedom. The church of God is the third category alongside ethnic Israel and the Gentile world — a sign that the church is a new creation community transcending ethnic distinctions while remaining in responsibility to all. Paul's example serves the inclusion of all into the family of Christ.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Just as I try to please everyone in everything I do, not seeking my own advantage, but that of many, that they may be saved.' Paul's apostolic principle of maximum adaptability for maximum salvation reach is the conclusion of the entire argument from 9:1. The kenotic pattern — not seeking one's own advantage but the other's — is the Christological form of apostolic mission. 'That they may be saved' is the ultimate Christological horizon: the salvation that Christ won is what apostolic sacrifice serves to extend. The apostle's self-emptying participates in and extends the redemptive logic of the cross.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH11 = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>'Be imitators of me, as I am of Christ.' The chain of imitation is explicitly Christological: believers imitate Paul; Paul imitates Christ. The apostle's kenotic mission-pattern (ch. 9), his voluntary limitation of rights, his 'becoming all things to all people' for the gospel — all of these are not original with Paul but derived from the pattern of the incarnate Son who 'came not to be served but to serve' (Mark 10:45). Christological discipleship is mimetic: transformation into the image of Christ by following those who have been transformed.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Now I commend you because you remember me in everything and maintain the traditions even as I delivered them to you.' The apostolic traditions (<em>paradoseis</em>) that Paul delivered are the same vocabulary as the reception-and-transmission of the resurrection tradition (15:3) and the Lord's Supper institution (11:23). These traditions are not Paul's inventions but the deposit of the Lord's own words and actions, transmitted through the apostolic chain. The Christ-community is defined by its fidelity to this transmitted tradition.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The head of every man is Christ, the head of a wife is her husband, and the head of God is Christ.' The Christological claim here is the foundation of the entire head-covering discussion: Christ is the <em>kephalē</em> (head) of every man. Headship in Pauline usage carries the sense of source, authority, and representative relationship — not domination but ordered, loving authority-with-responsibility. That Christ is head of 'every man' (not just believing men) extends his lordship to all humanity, though it is recognized only within the covenant community.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A man who prays or prophesies with his head covered 'dishonors his head.' The covering of the head that was an act of honor in Roman religious rites (the <em>capite velato</em> posture of the Roman pater familias at sacrifice) is reinterpreted in light of Christ's headship: for a man to veil his head in worship obscures the Christological glory that man as the image of Christ is to display. The creation-order argument that Paul develops in vv. 7-9 is rooted in man's relationship to Christ as his head.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A woman who prays or prophesies with her head uncovered 'dishonors her head.' The Corinthian context in which women prophesied (clearly assumed to be legitimate, not prohibited here) is significant: women in the new covenant community participated in vocal, public ministry before the congregation. The head covering for women is a sign of the creation order that contextualizes this Spirit-given ministry within the structure of covenantal relationship — affirming the ministry while situating it within the order Christ has established.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'For if a wife will not cover her head, then she should cut her hair short. But since it is disgraceful for a wife to cut her hair short or shave her head, let her cover her head.' The reductio ad absurdum argument: if covering the head is unnecessary, then the cultural marker of femininity (long hair) is equally unnecessary. The logic assumes that the social order communicating gender distinction and proper covenantal relationship is not arbitrary but reflects the created order that Christ's redeeming work restores and fulfills, not obliterates.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'For a man ought not to cover his head, since he is the image and glory of God.' Man as the image of God (<em>eikōn kai doxa Theou</em>) is the Genesis 1:26-27 basis for the head-covering argument. Christ, as the true image of God (Col 1:15; 2 Cor 4:4), is the archetype from which Adam's image-bearing derived its meaning. In worship, the man is to display this image-glory uncovered — reflecting the God whose image he bears. The created order is a Christological testimony: it was always pointing toward the one in whose image humanity was made.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'For man was not made from woman, but woman from man.' The Genesis 2 creation account — Adam formed first, Eve drawn from Adam — provides the created-order basis for the relational structure Paul is defending. The Christological application: just as woman's origin was from man, the church's origin is from Christ. The structural relationship of source-and-derived is not a hierarchy of value but of covenant order: the one who originates defines the relationship for the one who derives from him.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Neither was man created for woman, but woman for man.' The purposive statement from Genesis 2:18 ('it is not good for the man to be alone; I will make him a helper fit for him') grounds the relational ordering in God's creational purpose. The Christological parallel: the church was created for Christ — to be his body, his bride, his community of glory. Creation's purpose-structures are covenantal: the design reveals the relationship, and both testify to the Christ who was always their goal.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'That is why a wife ought to have a symbol of authority on her head, because of the angels.' The mysterious 'because of the angels' (<em>dia tous angelous</em>) has generated extensive interpretation. The most plausible background is the Jewish belief that angels attend worship and observe the order of God's covenant community (cf. 1QSa 2:8-9: the angels present in the assembly; Ps 138:1 LXX). The ordered worship of the church is a performance before cosmic witnesses — the angels who observe whether the community reflects the covenant order established in Christ.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Nevertheless, in the Lord woman is not independent of man nor man of woman.' The qualification is crucial: 'in the Lord' (<em>en kyriō</em>) — the christological sphere — the mutuality and interdependence of man and woman are fully affirmed. The creation-order argument does not establish male superiority but relational structure within mutual dependence. The new community in Christ is not a hierarchy of value but an ordered community of mutual need and mutual gift, where each serves the other's good.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'For as woman was made from man, so man is now born of woman. And all things are from God.' The circular mutual dependence — woman from man (creation), man from woman (birth) — and the ultimate divine source ('all things are from God') roots the entire creation-order argument in Christological theology. God, as creator and redeemer, is the source of all relational structure. The one through whom all things were created (8:6) has also ordered the covenantal relationships within which the church worships and reflects his glory.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Judge for yourselves: is it proper for a wife to pray to God with her head uncovered?' The appeal to the community's own judgment about propriety in worship echoes the wisdom appeal of 10:15. The Corinthians who prided themselves on spiritual discernment are invited to exercise that discernment about worship order. The question assumes a normative order of worship in which contextual appropriateness is not arbitrary but reflects the created and covenantal structures that Christ has established and redeemed.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Does not nature itself teach you that if a man wears long hair it is a disgrace for him?' The 'nature' (<em>physis</em>) argument — drawing on observable patterns of creation — was a standard Stoic and Jewish method of moral reasoning from the created order. Paul's use of natural observation alongside scriptural argument reflects the Reformed understanding of general revelation: creation itself testifies to God's design. The Christological underpinning is that creation reflects the creator whose image-structures are being displayed and reflected in ordered worship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'But if a woman has long hair, it is her glory? For her hair is given to her for a covering.' The natural hair-covering given to women as 'glory' (<em>doxa</em>) echoes the 'glory' language of vv. 7-8: man is the glory of God; woman is the glory of man; woman's hair is her glory. The creation gifts that express relational identity — the hair covering given by nature — are not accidental but embedded in the created order. The God who created these natural expressions of relational identity is the same God who establishes covenant worship order in Christ.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'If anyone is inclined to be contentious, we have no such custom, nor do the churches of God.' The apostolic appeal to universal church practice is a significant hermeneutical move: the ordering of worship is not a local Pauline preference but the common practice of all the churches of God. The Christological logic: the church universal, formed by the one gospel and the one Spirit, exhibits consistent patterns of worship that reflect the one Lord's ordering of his community. Contentious deviation from this common practice is not freedom but disorder.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'But in the following instructions I do not commend you, because when you come together it is not for the better but for the worse.' The Lord's Supper section begins with the most direct rebuke in the letter: the Corinthians' eucharistic practice is actually counter-productive — their gatherings make things worse rather than better. The meal that should be the highest expression of Christ-community (the body of Christ sharing in the body of Christ) has become a site of division, shame, and social hierarchy — the opposite of what the Lord's death proclaimed (v. 26).</p>",
    "18": "<p>'For, in the first place, when you come together as a church, I hear that there are divisions among you.' The divisions (<em>schismata</em>) in the Corinthian gathering — the same word as 1:10 — now manifest at the Lord's Supper table, the one place where unity should be most visible. The social stratification of Corinthian society (wealthy members bringing lavish meals, poor members bringing little or nothing) is being replicated at the table of the one who 'though he was rich became poor' for them (2 Cor 8:9). The eucharist is being un-christologized by class distinction.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'For there must be factions among you in order that those who are genuine among you may be recognized.' The 'necessity' (<em>dei</em>) of factions echoes apocalyptic language about the eschatological testing that reveals genuine faith. God's providential ordering of even the church's failures serves the purpose of making visible who truly belongs to Christ. The genuine (<em>dokimoi</em>) are revealed through the crisis — those who, even in the disordered Corinthian situation, preserve the eucharistic meaning by waiting for one another and honoring the poor.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'When you come together, it is not the Lord's Supper that you eat.' The devastating verdict: what the Corinthians are doing when they 'come together' does not constitute the Lord's Supper. The Lord's Supper requires that the death of the Lord be proclaimed (v. 26) — but a meal where the wealthy eat their fill while the poor go hungry proclaims not the Lord's self-giving but the world's self-keeping. The form of the meal has been evacuated of its Christological content by the social practice surrounding it.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'For in eating, each one goes ahead with his own meal. One goes hungry, another gets drunk.' The specific abuse: the wealthy arrived early and ate their privately-brought food (Corinthian practice at communal meals was to bring food proportional to one's status), while the working poor who arrived late found nothing and watched the wealthy drunk. The class-stratified Roman meal custom, imported into the Christian gathering, contradicted the Lord's Supper's essential declaration that the one body of Christ shares in the one sacrifice equally.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'What! Do you not have houses to eat and drink in? Or do you despise the church of God and humiliate those who have nothing?' Paul's question exposes the theological stakes: treating the poor with contempt at the Lord's table is despising the church of God — the community bought by Christ's blood (6:20; 7:23). The poor in the Corinthian community are members of the body of Christ (12:12-27); shaming them at the eucharist is shaming Christ himself in the members of his body.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'For I received from the Lord what I also delivered to you, that the Lord Jesus on the night when he was betrayed took bread.' The institution narrative is introduced as something 'received from the Lord' — apostolic tradition with the highest possible authority. The specific detail 'on the night when he was betrayed' (<em>en tē nykti hē paredideto</em>) grounds the eucharist in the concrete historical moment of the passion. The meal is not a timeless spiritual ritual but a specific memorial of a specific night when the covenant Lord was handed over for the sins of his people.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'This is my body which is for you. Do this in remembrance of me.' The institution of the bread-as-body contains the self-interpretive word of the Lord: 'for you' (<em>hyper hymōn</em>) — the substitutionary/representative character of his death. The 'remembrance' (<em>anamnēsis</em>) is not mere mental recollection but covenantal re-presentation — the memorial that makes present the saving event it recalls, as the Passover Seder re-presented the exodus for each generation. Every eucharist is a participation in the once-for-all sacrifice 'for you.'</p>",
    "25": "<p>'This cup is the new covenant in my blood. Do this, as often as you drink it, in remembrance of me.' The new covenant (<em>kainē diathēkē</em>) in Christ's blood fulfills and surpasses the Mosaic covenant ratified by the blood of bulls and goats (Exod 24:8). Jeremiah 31:31-34 promised a new covenant with different terms: not written on stone but on hearts; not requiring daily sacrifice but with sins forgiven once-for-all. The cup of the Lord's Supper is the enacted proclamation that this new covenant has been inaugurated in Christ's death — the cup of the new age.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Whoever, therefore, eats the bread or drinks the cup of the Lord in an unworthy manner will be guilty concerning the body and blood of the Lord.' The high Christological stakes of eucharistic participation: unworthy eating is not disrespect for a ritual but participation in the guilt of those who crucified the Lord. The body and blood of Christ present at the table make the table a place where the death and resurrection of Christ are enacted — to participate carelessly is to join the ranks of those who dismissed the Son of God. The <em>anamnesis</em> makes the past event contemporaneous with the present community.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Let a person examine himself, then, and so eat of the bread and drink of the cup.' The self-examination required before eucharistic participation is the Christological discipline of discernment: does this eating-and-drinking proclaim the Lord's death, or does it contradict it? The examination is not perfectionist self-scrutiny but orientation-check: am I approaching this table as one who depends on Christ's body given for me, or am I treating it as a social occasion? The sacrament requires a consistent Christological consciousness.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'For anyone who eats and drinks without discerning the body eats and drinks judgment on himself.' 'Discerning the body' (<em>diakrinōn to sōma</em>) most likely refers both to the eucharistic body of Christ (present in the bread) and the ecclesial body of Christ (present in the gathered poor who are being shamed). Failing to discern the body of Christ in both its dimensions — the sacramental and the social — brings divine judgment. The Christological unity of the eucharistic and ecclesial body is the ground of Paul's entire argument in this section.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'That is why many of you are weak and ill, and some have died.' The physical consequences (weakness, illness, death) are divine judgment on eucharistic abuse. Paul interprets the community's health crises in a Christological frame: the Lord who disciplines those he loves (Heb 12:6; Prov 3:12) visits judgment on those who desecrate the body and blood that are the very means of their salvation. The judgment is not retributive destruction but corrective discipline, as v. 32 will clarify: 'judged by the Lord so that we may not be condemned along with the world.'</p>",
    "31": "<p>'But if we judged ourselves truly, we would not be judged.' The self-examination called for in v. 28 is the preventive form of the judgment that God otherwise imposes. The Christological logic: Christ has already borne the ultimate judgment for sin on the cross; the Christian who appropriately applies that judgment to himself ('yes, I am a sinner who needs this sacrifice') is already participating in the cross's verdict and needs no additional judgment. Self-examination is the individual application of the cross's logic.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'But when we are judged by the Lord, we are disciplined so that we may not be condemned along with the world.' The distinction between divine discipline and eschatological condemnation is crucial: the illness and death of v. 30 are not signs of divine rejection but of fatherly correction (cf. Heb 12:7-11). The goal of the discipline is inclusion in the final salvation, not exclusion. Christ who bore the condemnation of the world (Rom 8:3) ensures that those who belong to him receive discipline rather than condemnation — even severe discipline serves their ultimate good.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'So then, my brothers, when you come together to eat, wait for one another.' The practical Christological application: the cure for the eucharistic disorder is waiting — waiting as the most basic act of mutual regard. The wealthy who arrive early and eat their fill before the poor arrive must wait. Waiting for one another at the Lord's table enacts the Christological principle that all members of the body are equally dependent on the one who died for them. The meal that proclaims the Lord's death must embody the Lord's death in its practice of self-giving.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'If anyone is hungry, let him eat at home, so that when you come together it will not be for judgment.' The Lord's Supper is not a meal for satisfying hunger — that is what homes are for. The gathering of the church is specifically for the proclamation of the Lord's death (v. 26), for sharing in his body and blood (10:16), and for forming the one body of Christ (10:17). Separating the eucharistic meal from ordinary social dining preserves the Christological meaning of what the church does when it gathers — it gathers around the crucified and risen Lord, not around social status.</p>"
  }
}

